---
import PostAuthorBio from "../../components/PostAuthorBio.astro";
import PostCommunityCta from "../../components/PostCommunityCta.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const title = "What happens when students from 14 undergraduate majors build software with Codex";
const description =
  "A reflection on a course where students from different majors used Codex to turn everyday problems into working prototypes.";
const pubDate = new Date("2026-07-01T12:00:00-04:00");
const formatDate = new Intl.DateTimeFormat("en-US", {
  day: "numeric",
  month: "long",
  year: "numeric",
});
const siteUrl = Astro.site ?? new URL("https://codexparatodos.com");
const canonical = new URL("/blog/x-tech-21-showcase-exploratec-en/", siteUrl).href;
---

<SiteLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical={canonical}
  ogType="article"
  lang="en"
  robots="noindex, nofollow"
>
  <main>
    <article class="post-page container">
      <a class="back-link" href="/blog/">Back to blog</a>
      <header class="post-header">
        <time datetime={pubDate.toISOString()}>
          {formatDate.format(pubDate)}
        </time>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p>{description}</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-content">
        <p>
          This semester I taught XTECC21: "Create your own agent: automate your day-to-day work."
          It is a course in <a href="https://exploratec.udd.cl/">ExploraTech</a>, a program from the
          Faculty of Engineering at Universidad del Desarrollo, but it is open to students from every
          major on campus. That is why the room had students from engineering, design, dentistry,
          psychology, architecture, law, medical technology and other areas.
        </p>

        <p>
          The course began with an introduction to generative artificial intelligence and the use of
          <a href="https://chatgpt.com/">ChatGPT</a>. Then we moved to
          <a href="https://openai.com/codex/">Codex</a>. The question was why we needed a tool like
          that if we already had chatbots that could write, summarize and answer questions.
        </p>

        <p>
          The answer has to do with a skill we have developed for decades: operating computational
          devices. We open programs, copy data, fill out forms, rename files, review spreadsheets,
          upload documents, click through menus and repeat whole sequences of work.
        </p>

        <p>
          Automating those operations has always been possible. The problem was the cost. You had to
          know how to program, understand the system, write scripts, test them and maintain them. With
          agentic tools like Codex, that boundary moves. A student can describe what they want to
          achieve, and the agent programs what is needed to move closer to that result.
        </p>

        <p>
          Most students did not have prior programming experience. So the course had to start from a
          different place. Before looking at files or technical decisions, they needed to learn how to
          formulate, narrow the scope, test what Codex returned and decide when the result was useful.
        </p>

        <h2>Three weeks to turn an idea into software</h2>

        <p>
          The course lasted three months, with two sessions each week. There were written exams to
          assess concepts, but the final stretch was practical.
        </p>

        <p>
          During the last three weeks, I asked students to find a problem that could be solved with an
          app, software or an agent. The prompt was deliberately broad. I wanted to see what problems
          appeared when the starting point was the students' own routines, not an assignment designed
          by the professor.
        </p>

        <p>
          The classes during those weeks were shorter. I introduced one technical piece, and then we
          worked on the projects. We covered the basics of
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vibe_coding">vibe coding</a>, publishing with
          <a href="https://vercel.com/">Vercel</a>, login with
          <a href="https://firebase.google.com/">Firebase</a> and other pieces the demos needed to
          reach a good finish.
        </p>

        <p>
          The most important work happened in the guidance. Each student had a different need. Some
          needed to bring an idea that was too large down to a first version. Others needed to
          understand why their app was not saving data. Others wanted to connect APIs, clean up an
          interface, add authentication or prepare a demo that would not break during the presentation.
        </p>

        <p>
          That one-on-one work was demanding, but it was also where the course began to show its
          value. Students were working with a new tool, their own expectations and the limits of time.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/calendaris-01-portada.png" alt="Calendaris cover with an academic calendar and access panel" />
          <figcaption>Calendaris starts from a very local need: a calendar that understands how academic life is organized at the university.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Big problems, small problems, specific software</h2>

        <p>
          One of the projects in the showcase is
          <a href="https://calendaris-inky.vercel.app/">Calendaris</a>, by Nicolás Soto. The idea
          sounds simple: a university calendar. But that simplicity is misleading.
        </p>

        <p>
          There are many calendar apps. None speak exactly the language of these students. At the
          university, semesters, bimesters, trimesters, major-specific combinations and different ways
          of organizing evaluations all coexist. Calendaris takes that specific need and turns it into
          a tool designed for that context.
        </p>

        <p>
          I care a lot about that kind of problem. A good app does not always need a universal idea.
          Sometimes it begins because someone understands a routine better than any generic piece of
          software does.
        </p>

        <p>
          <a href="https://study-brain-cniico.vercel.app">StudyBrain</a>, by Nicolás Campos, goes in
          another direction. I describe it as a CRM for students. It centralizes grades, topics,
          evaluations and weekly plans. What stands out is that Nicolás is a first-year computer
          science student, and he already has users using the system.
        </p>

        <p>
          There is also a second layer: StudyBrain is designed for humans and agents. Nicolás has a
          plugin for Codex and Claude Code that lets students manage academic needs from those tools.
          That detail shows where this kind of software can go. An app can be prepared for people
          clicking through it and for agents operating on top of it.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/studybrain-01-portada.png" alt="StudyBrain agents view" />
          <figcaption>StudyBrain works as a personal academic management system and also leaves room for agents connected to the academic workflow.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <a href="https://brief-lab.vercel.app">BriefLab</a>, by Amelia Troncoso, is another case I
          like a lot. Amelia comes from design, not programming. That shows, in the best way. The app
          has visual taste, care and a clear idea: generating fictional briefs to practice design and
          build a portfolio without depending on real clients.
        </p>

        <p>
          Codex provides part of the technical execution. Amelia provides the design judgment. That
          combination is one of the best signals from the course. When an agentic tool lowers the cost
          of building, taste and domain knowledge matter more.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/brieflab-02-flujo.png" alt="BriefLab area selection flow" />
          <figcaption>BriefLab shows something I care about: a student without a programming focus using Codex to turn design judgment into software.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <a href="https://finex-public-frontend.vercel.app">FinEx</a>, by Sebastián Ramírez, tackles
          personal finance. It is an area with many existing apps, but this project has a different
          force because it comes from a real practice. Sebastián had been organizing his finances in
          Excel and brought that logic into an app with Gmail import, expense classification and
          budget visualization.
        </p>

        <p>
          It also has users. He uses it himself. Other people can try it. The point is to turn a
          personal finance workflow into a clearer, shareable and well-finished product.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/finex-02-demo-dashboard.png" alt="FinEx dashboard with a financial summary" />
          <figcaption>FinEx turns a personal way of organizing expenses into an app other people can use.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Fit Me, by Diego Rivera and Valentina Castillo, is perhaps the most conceptual project of
          the group. Instead of a public web app, it is an automation that runs on Sundays on its
          creators' computer and prepares seven weekly outfits using real clothes, style references
          and weather.
        </p>

        <p>
          I find it powerful for one reason: it shows that software can also be private, specific and
          small. No one would have funded a large platform to solve exactly that need. Before, it
          would have been too expensive to build something like that for one person. With agents, that
          cost drops enough for it to be worth doing.
        </p>

        <p>
          And it is fine that it stays private. Clothes, weather, calendars and personal preferences
          do not have to become a startup. They can become an automation that makes someone's day a
          little happier.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/fit-me-02-propuesta-final.jpg" alt="Visual result of weekly outfits generated by Fit Me" />
          <figcaption>Fit Me takes personal software to a clear edge case: a private automation for deciding what to wear during the week.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <a href="https://rubricacheck-mvp.vercel.app">RubricaCheck</a>, by José Tomás Cifuentes,
          closes the selection well. José Tomás studies civil engineering. His problem is concrete:
          professors give students rubrics and instructions, and students often need to translate that
          material into clear criteria for preparing a submission.
        </p>

        <p>
          RubricaCheck turns rubrics and instructions into a more manageable structure. It uses the
          Gemini API and has a complete flow. I like it because it does not try to do everything. It
          takes a common academic friction and makes it workable.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/demo-screenshots/rubricacheck-02-ejemplo-o-formulario.png" alt="Loaded example in RubricaCheck" />
          <figcaption>RubricaCheck turns a rubric into a clearer workflow for preparing a submission.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Teaching while the tool changes</h2>

        <p>
          The biggest challenge in the course was teaching something that was moving a lot while we
          were teaching it.
        </p>

        <p>
          The <a href="https://openai.com/index/introducing-the-codex-app/">Codex app</a> was very
          recent. We lived through multiple model changes, and several features transformed
          radically along the way.
        </p>

        <p>
          That made the course harder and more fun. We had to adjust examples, expectations and ways
          of working as we went. Sometimes an instruction that had required several steps began to
          resolve more directly. Other times, new errors appeared. Students had to learn in an
          unstable environment, similar to the workplace they will encounter.
        </p>

        <p>
          That was another idea I wanted to give them. Whether their major includes programming or
          not, they need to get used to working in this new professional environment. An environment
          where part of the work is delegated to systems that read, write, program, test and operate.
          The advantage is not in knowing how to press more buttons. It is in understanding what to
          ask for, how to evaluate what comes back and when to intervene.
        </p>

        <h2>Presenting the projects to the community</h2>

        <p>
          After the final exam, I invited six projects to present to the community at the
          <a href="https://codexparatodos.com/showcase/">ExploraTech Showcase</a>, an in-person
          technology fair inside the university. If you follow the link, you can review the projects
          in detail.
        </p>

        <p>
          Seen together, these projects say something about the moment we are in. A student can get
          much faster to a first working version, but the work does not disappear. You have to choose
          better problems, formulate better, test more and have the judgment not to accept every
          output from the agent. That is why the phrase I repeated most during the course still feels
          useful to me: moving at machine speed, but with human judgment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <PostAuthorBio lang="en" />
    </article>

    <PostCommunityCta lang="en" />
  </main>
</SiteLayout>
